tags: peter parker: the spectacular spider man
summary: There seems to be a trend (if two examples makes a trend. Which they don’t.) of Spider-Man writers getting to right a final...
body:
There seems to be a trend (if two examples makes a trend. Which they don’t.) of Spider-Man writers getting to right a final issue love letter to the character. Dan Slott wrote a nice summation of what he saw as Spider-Man in the final issue of his years long run on the character, and here Zdarsky does a similar thing (after a much shorter run).

What makes both of these issues enjoyable is that they step away from any ongoing plots or setting up the next storyline and just look at Peter Parker and what makes him a great character. The fact that each writer is able to show a different facet of the hero is a confirmation that there are still depths there for creators to mine. It would likely soon get wearing if everyone got the opportunity to tell a tale like this, but by taking time out rather than just moving on to the next writer (as has pretty much been the case in work for hire superhero comics since they started), it makes a series feel less of a commercial endeavour and instead suggest that it has some interest in catering to both fans and creators, leaving them space for some character moments instead of insisting they carry on hurtling towards Spider-Geddon or whatever.

Zdarsky looks at Spider-Man’s impact on people’s lives and- in keeping with the general rules of Parker luck- this isn’t without tragedy. Yet what matters most is that even when there is tragedy, he brings good to people’s lives, and not always through the expected super-heroic ways- taking the time out of his life to tutor a kid to stop him heading in the wrong direction in terms of life choices has more value than punching someone or shooting webs while cracking wise. It’s a nice reminder that behind all the action and the time travel and the drama there’s someone that just wants to help everyone he can, however he can, which says more about his value as a character in the Marvel Universe than any number of epic adventures ever could.

From Peter Parker: The Spectacular Spider-Man 310, by Chip Zdarsky & Travis Lanham
